'''''Dark Forces: Jedi Knight''''' is the third and final volume in the [[Star Wars: Dark Forces (novellas)|''Dark Forces'']] trilogy of novellas written by [[William C. Dietz]]. It was originally released on [[October 14]], [[1998]] by [[Dark Horse Comics]] and [[Berkley Boulevard|Boulevard]]. Both the hardcover and trade paperback include twenty-five full-color illustrations by [[Dave Dorman]].

==Publisher's summary==
===Hardcover===
====Back cover====
''[[Kyle Katarn]], [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel]] agent and novice [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]], has just returned from his covert operation to find the location of the [[Valley of the Jedi]]. But he knows that the evil [[Jerec (Inquisitor)|Jerec]], a [[Dark Jedi/Legends|dark Jedi]] with designs on the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Empire's]] throne, knows where the Valley is too. Upon returning to the Alliance, and with the support of [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] himself, Kyle offers to find the Valley and stop the oncoming Imperial invasion—and, at last, fulfill his destiny as a Jedi.''

''Based on the popular [[Star Wars: Dark Forces|''Star Wars: DARK FORCES'']] and [[Star Wars: Jedi Knight: Dark Forces II|''Star Wars: JEDI KNIGHT'']] interactive games, ''Jedi Knight'' is part three of a trilogy written by acclaimed author [[William C. Dietz]] (''Steelheart'') and illustrated by award-winning ''[[Star Wars]]'' cover artist [[Dave Dorman]]''.

====Inside flap====
''The dark Jedi Jerec continues his search for the legendary Valley of the Jedi and sends his Imperial minions to invade the remote [[Planet/Legends|planet]] on which it is hidden. But the Valley's location is also known to Kyle Katarn, who has returned with [[Jan Ors]] and Luke Skywalker from their secret mission. Kyle proposes that he and Jan sneak onto the planet and stop the Empire themselves, which leads to his most dangerous—and important—mission yet.''

''This brand-new adventure trilogy provides background to, and incorporates elements of, the [[LucasArts]] ''DARK FORCES'' and ''JEDI KNIGHT'' interactive games. ''Jedi Knight'' completes the trilogy begun in [[Dark Forces: Soldier for the Empire|''Soldier for the Empire'']] and continued in [[Dark Forces: Rebel Agent|''Rebel Agent'']]''.

===Trade paperback===
Now available in trade paperback, this graphic-story album—a prose novella with twenty-five full-page painted illustrations—concludes the sweeping trilogy based on characters and events introduced in the popular [[Star Wars: Dark Forces|''Dark Forces'']] interactive games. ''Jedi Knight'' chronicles the adventures of Rebel agent Kyle Katarn as he seeks to prevent the legendary Valley of the Jedi from falling into the hands of the Empire's Jerec, a dark Jedi who plans to harness the unbelievable power of the Valley for his own ends.

''Kyle Katarn, Rebel Agent and novice Jedi, has discovered the location of the legendary Valley of the Jedi. But Jerec, a dark Jedi seeking to dethrone the [[Emperor/Legends|Emperor]], orders an Imperial invasion against the world where the Valley is hidden.''

''With the support of Luke Skywalker, Kyle volunteers to sneak onto the planet and stop the Empire before they can find the Valley in his most dangerous—and important—mission yet.''

''A mission that presents the opportunity, at long last, for Kyle to fulfill his destiny as a Jedi.''

==Plot summary==
Having found the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] that is home to the [[Valley of the Jedi]], [[Jerec (Inquisitor)|Jerec]] dispatches [[Probe droid/Legends|probe droids]] to [[Ruusan/Legends|Ruusan]], followed by an envoy of [[Dark Jedi/Legends|Dark Jedi]] consisting of [[Boc Aseca|Boc]], [[Sariss]] and [[Yun]]. They destroy a fugitive [[City/Legends|settlement]] in their search for the ancient ruins, while Jerec's [[Imperial-class Star Destroyer/Legends|Star Destroyer]], [[Vengeance (Imperial-class, Jerec)|''Vengeance'']], [[Blockade/Legends|blockades]] the planet. [[Kyle Katarn]] and [[Jan Ors]] continue their search for the Valley. The [[Agent/Legends|agents]] pose as [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperials]] aboard a captured [[Transport/Legends|transport]] to bypass the Ruusan blockade and take their [[Starship/Legends|ship]], the [[Moldy Crow/Legends|''Moldy Crow'']], to the surface of the planet. On Ruusan, Jerec has begun an extensive excavation searching for powerful relics of the [[Seventh Battle of Ruusan|ancient Jedi battle]]. Kyle and Jan infiltrate Jerec's operation, but are separated. Imperials take Jan hostage.

Kyle battles his way through Jerec's defenses, treading dangerously close to the [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark side]] as he aggressively defeats the Dark Jedi [[Maw (Dark Jedi)|Maw]] in revenge for his [[Parent|father's]] [[Death/Legends|death]]. When Kyle is knocked unconscious by Jerec after refusing to turn to the dark side, he experiences a [[Force vision/Legends|vision]] of the Battle of Ruusan. Kyle witness the actions of [[Tal (Jedi)|Tal]], a loyal follower of [[General/Legends|General]] [[Hoth (Jedi Lord)|Hoth]], as the [[Army of Light/Legends|Army of Light]] confronts the [[Brotherhood of Darkness/Legends|Brotherhood of Darkness]]. Tal's consciousness, along with all Jedi, is swept into the [[Thought bomb|thought bomb weapon]] unleashed by the Brotherhood.

Awakening from his dream, Kyle battles Sariss. A conflicted Yun, who recalls how Kyle spared his life on [[Sulon/Legends|Sulon]], stops her [[Lightsaber/Legends|blade]]. Sariss cuts down Yun, and Kyle picks up Yun's fallen blade as his own. With it, he defeats Sariss and, later, Boc. When he finally battles Jerec, Kyle disarms the Dark Jedi. Jerec demands that Kyle give in to dark temptation and slay him. Instead Kyle returns Jerec's lightsaber and strikes him down in [[Lightsaber combat/Legends|combat]]. With the villains defeated, Kyle frees the [[Force ghost/Legends|spirits]] contained in the thought bomb, dispersing the focus of [[The Force/Legends|Force]] energy beyond the Valley and finally bringing peace to these long [[Torture/Legends|tortured]] souls.

==Continuity==
The account of the [[Seventh Battle of Ruusan]] in this book differed somewhat from the more detailed account told in the [[2006]] novel ''[[Darth Bane: Path of Destruction]]'', though ''Dark Forces: Jedi Knight'' was published several years earlier. It is difficult to tell which account was [[Star Wars Legends|canon]]; the account in this book took place through a [[Force vision/Legends|dream vision]] given to [[Kyle Katarn]] as he was knocked unconscious. He saw the events from the perspective of the [[Human/Legends|human]] [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Tal (Jedi)|Tal]], who was close to [[General/Legends|General]] [[Hoth (Jedi Lord)|Hoth]], but was not mentioned in any other source. Notably, in this book the [[thought bomb]] was prepared by [[Skere Kaan|Kaan's]] [[Brotherhood of Darkness/Legends|Brotherhood]] in advance of the [[Army of Light/Legends|Army of Light's]] arrival, and the scene took place in a valley. In the other, it took place deep in a [[Cave/Legends|cave]] and the bomb was simultaneously created and detonated. The Jedi happen to enter the cave just as the bomb was about to be detonated.

There was no mention of the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] in the novel. [[Mon Mothma/Legends|Mon Mothma]] was again functioning as a leading figure, but her capacity as the Republic's [[Chief of State (New Republic)/Legends|Chief of State]]<ref name="TNEC" /> was not mentioned. The narration and the dialogues use the more familiar terms "Empire" (instead of "[[Imperial Remnant]]") and "[[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Alliance]]"/"Rebels".

In this novella, [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa]] was referred to as Leia Organa Solo, a name she would not take until [[8 ABY/Legends|three years later]].<ref name="TNEC">''[[The New Essential Chronology]]''</ref>

